10 SECTION 2. Section 5 of chapter 131 of the General Laws as appearing in the 2022
11 Official Edition, is hereby amended by inserting after the second paragraph the following
12 paragraph:-
13 The hunting of deer by bow and arrow shall be permitted on any date, including a Sunday
14 or legal holiday, that the director declares as an open season for such hunting. Except as
15 otherwise provided in the preceding paragraph, an open season declared by the director for the
16 hunting of deer by bow and arrow, which open season period occurs in whole or in part, within
17 the last 3 months of the calendar year, shall be for a period of not less than 7 days that shall be
18 consecutive.
19 SECTION 3. Section 57 of said chapter 131, as so appearing, is hereby amended by
20 inserting at the end of the paragraph the following sentence:- Notwithstanding, this section shall
21 not prohibit or render unlawful, the hunting of deer by bow and arrow or the carrying on his
22 person a bow and arrow for the purpose of hunting deer, during any Sunday declared as an open
23 season for such hunting, by the director with the approval of the fisheries and wildlife board.
24 SECTION 4. Said Chapter 131 of the General Laws, as so appearing, is hereby amended
25 by striking out section 5C and inserting in place thereof the following section:-
26 Section 5C. The citizens of the commonwealth shall have the right to harvest fish and
27 wildlife free from harassment subject to rules and regulations established to maintain sustainable
28 and healthy populations of such natural resources.
29 (a) No person shall obstruct, interfere with or otherwise prevent the lawful harvest of fish
30 and wildlife by another at any such place in the commonwealth where it is lawful to do so. It
31 shall be a violation of this section for a person to intentionally:
2 of 6

32 (1) drive or disturb fish or wildlife for the purpose of interrupting a lawful taking; or
33 (2) block, follow, impede or otherwise harass another who is engaged in the lawful taking
34 of fish or wildlife; or
35 (3) use natural or artificial visual, aural, olfactory or physical stimulus to effect wildlife in
36 order to hinder or prevent such taking; or
37 (4) erect barriers with the intent to deny ingress or egress to areas where the lawful taking
38 of wildlife may occur; or
39 (5) interject himself into the line of fire; or
40 (6) effect the condition or placement of personal or public property intended for use in
41 the taking of wildlife; or
42 (7) enter or remain upon public lands, or upon private lands without the permission of the
43 owner or his agent, with intent to violate this section; or
44 (8) verbally or physically harass, threaten or other means of intimidation of an
45 individual/s lawfully engaged in the harvest fish and wildlife;
46 (9) utilize mechanical aerial devices to drive wildlife, harass, film, photograph or
47 otherwise intimidate.
48 A violation of this paragraph shall be punished by imprisonment in a jail or house of
49 correction for not more than 1 year or by a fine of not more than $1,000 or both.
50 (b) Any person having caused destruction or otherwise vandalizes equipment utilized,
51 directly or indirectly, for the lawful harvest of fish and wildlife including, but not limited to,
3 of 6

52 vehicles, blinds, stands, trail cams, fishing gear, boats, etc. shall be punished by imprisonment in
53 a jail or house of correction for not more than 2 years or by a fine of not more than $5,000 or
54 both.
55 (c) Any person having caused bodily injuries of another that were sustained from any
56 type of harassment or vandalism covered under this section shall be punished by imprisonment in
57 a jail or house of correction for not more than 5 years or by a fine of not more than $10,000 or
58 both.
59 The superior court shall have jurisdiction to issue an injunction to enjoin any such
60 conduct or conspiracy in violation of the provisions of this section. A person who sustains
61 damage as a result of any act which is in violation of this section may bring a civil action for
62 punitive damages in addition to the penalties established herein. Environmental protection
63 officers and other law enforcement officers with arrest powers shall be authorized to enforce the
64 provisions of this section.
65 (d) Unless authorized by the property owner it shall be unlawful to post land closed, or
66 restricted, to the lawful harvest of fish and wildlife. Any person convicted of illegally posting
67 land shall be punished by imprisonment in a jail or house of correction for not more than 1 year
68 or a fine of not more $1,000 or both.
69 Any fines collected under this section shall be deposited into the Inland Fisheries and
70 Game Fund established under section 2C of chapter 131, and may be utilized for the purposes of
71 the Hunter Education Program.
